00:00:48.110 --> 00:00:49.443
but from a policy point of view.

00:00:49.443 --> 00:00:52.810
Because I think what you've done
is given the world the ability

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:55.890
to communicate in so
many different ways here,

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:57.640
and so I want you
to put your brains

00:00:57.640 --> 00:00:59.015
to the problem I'm going
to throw at you today,

00:00:59.015 --> 00:01:01.310
which is some of the problems
we're going to be facing

00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:03.610
and we're going to be
facing the next 10, 20, 30

00:01:03.610 --> 00:01:04.910
years going forward.

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:06.969
A couple things just about me.

00:01:06.969 --> 00:01:09.260
I'm going to talk about the
medicine of exercise today.

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:10.780
I have a website here.

00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:12.780
I have a signup, if you're
interested in getting

00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:14.321
our newsletters on
preventive health,

00:01:14.321 --> 00:01:16.120
and I send out
about four a year.

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:19.830
Also I'm pretty
active in Twitter

00:01:19.830 --> 00:01:22.000
and send out different
information on that.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:23.920
What I'm here to tell
you guys and what

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:28.165
I'm going to be pushing today
is what we call get off your,

00:01:28.165 --> 00:01:31.990
I guess, couch, we'll say,
get off your couch medicine.

00:01:31.990 --> 00:01:35.600
You guys are going to help
me get this message out

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:39.492
on the importance of activity
and exercise as a medicine.

00:01:39.492 --> 00:01:41.450
And it's an interesting
kind of paradigm shift.

00:01:41.450 --> 00:01:44.300
"The Exercise Cure" is
a book which, I think,

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:48.225
really it was an interesting
way to pitch this.

00:01:48.225 --> 00:01:49.100
I did it with Rodale.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:52.444
Because the "Home Remedies" book
was very successful and kind

00:01:52.444 --> 00:01:54.610
of, all right, I'm a runner,
and I have a hurt knee,

00:01:54.610 --> 00:01:56.810
and I need to do these
exercises to fix my knee.

00:01:56.810 --> 00:01:59.830
This is a conceptual book
about looking and changing

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:01.890
the way people think
about exercise.

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:04.720
I gave a lecture last
month at Cornell Med School

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:07.590
to the second year med
students on exercise.

00:02:07.590 --> 00:02:10.229
Now you'd think that this
being, as I'll go through,

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:11.652
a very powerful
drug people would

00:02:11.652 --> 00:02:12.860
hear about this all the time.

00:02:12.860 --> 00:02:15.750
In the 200-plus history of
Cornell Med School, that

00:02:15.750 --> 00:02:20.147
was the first lecture they'd
ever had on exercise ever.

00:02:20.147 --> 00:02:21.980
As I'll talk about, the
whole medical system

00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:24.870
is set up to treat disease,
and it's very poorly

00:02:24.870 --> 00:02:26.450
set up to encourage wellness.

00:02:26.450 --> 00:02:29.380
And so number one
is-- and I want

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:32.040
to make sure that nobody
in your guys' world

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:35.980
is this person who is basically
so focused on whatever

00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:38.240
it is they're doing
they're not moving.

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:40.450
And the concept here is
that across the spectrum

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:43.970
of the human condition there's
no more powerful, potent,

00:02:43.970 --> 00:02:46.650
and effective medicine
than exercise.

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:48.699
And so I'm just going
to go through relatively

00:02:48.699 --> 00:02:49.740
quickly some information.

00:02:49.740 --> 00:02:51.940
This study published this
year just a couple months ago

00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:53.314
in a journal called
"Circulation"

00:02:53.314 --> 00:02:55.460
from the American
Heart Association,

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:58.310
looking at men greater
than 45 years of age,

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:01.040
a prospective study, which
is the best kind in medicine,

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:03.990
looking at the effects of heart
failure and what causes that.

00:03:03.990 --> 00:03:06.160
And not surprisingly,
sitting around on your butt

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:08.087
all the time and not
moving correlates

00:03:08.087 --> 00:03:09.920
to a much higher incidence
of heart failure.

00:03:09.920 --> 00:03:12.378
So it's not good for your heart,
and this is the number one

00:03:12.378 --> 00:03:13.950
killer in the United States.

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:17.580
Now the concept of movement
for activity and for health

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:21.000
and for just a better
balanced life is nothing new.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.800
The ancient Greeks
and the ancient Romans

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:25.270
knew that to be sound in mind
and body those things work

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:25.770
together.

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:29.514
So the concept of dumb jock,
it's not really true, in fact.

00:03:29.514 --> 00:03:31.680
In fact, even from the high
school and middle school

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:33.840
levels, people who are
active and involved in sports

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:35.880
have everything from higher
self-esteem to higher health

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:38.088
profiles as they go into
adolescence and young adult.

00:03:38.088 --> 00:03:40.602
So basically activity is
something that starts young.

00:03:40.602 --> 00:03:42.560
We do a lot of preventive
strengthening classes

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:45.140
with kids, and getting kids
interested and involved

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:47.590
in athletics at a
young age it correlates

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:50.111
to a number of good
things as they go forward.

00:03:50.111 --> 00:03:51.860
So there's a big study
published last year

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:53.680
in the "Journal of American
Medical Association,"

00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:55.570
called "JAMA," and in
this study they looked

00:03:55.570 --> 00:03:58.257
at the anatomy of the
health care system.

00:03:58.257 --> 00:03:59.090
Now a couple things.

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:01.070
Number one, we've more
than doubled the money

00:04:01.070 --> 00:04:03.650
we're spending as
a product of GDP.

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:07.810
We spend about 18% of our GDP,
about $2.7 to $2.8 trillion

00:04:07.810 --> 00:04:08.582
a year.

00:04:08.582 --> 00:04:10.040
Just to put that
in context, that's

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:13.830
more than the GDP of most
every country in the world,

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:18.130
so it's a lot of money we're
spending on health care.

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:20.579
Government funding has
increased to about 42%

00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:23.370
of health care costs,
about $325 billion of which

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:25.520
are spent on
prescription medications.

00:04:25.520 --> 00:04:28.350
And surprisingly
people think that it's

00:04:28.350 --> 00:04:31.950
old people that cost the system
money, but it's really not.

00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:33.880
It's overweight
people, inactive people

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:36.416
cost the system by
far the most money.

00:04:36.416 --> 00:04:37.540
And it's also young people.

00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:40.390
So 85% of the medical
costs are under 65,

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:42.480
and a large majority
of that, about 60%,

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:44.600
are related to the effects
of inactivity, obesity,

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:48.760
heart disease, diabetes, et
cetera, so 65% of that spending

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:49.260
costs.

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:52.810
So basically, our
country needs to move.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:55.640
And as we'll get talking
about technology,

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:57.280
you guys have been
helpful in starting

00:04:57.280 --> 00:04:59.910
to get different apps and
things that encourage and track

00:04:59.910 --> 00:05:00.630
movement.

00:05:00.630 --> 00:05:02.450
I want to bring those
into the discussion

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:05.734
on encouraging
movement as policy.

00:05:05.734 --> 00:05:07.150
So we have this
health care system

00:05:07.150 --> 00:05:10.910
which throws huge amounts of
money at disease treatment.

00:05:10.910 --> 00:05:15.120
The concept is that basically
the worse the medical problem

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:16.240
the more the system pays.

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:17.906
So if you're somebody
that goes into see

00:05:17.906 --> 00:05:20.132
or your parents go see
somebody for their heart exam

00:05:20.132 --> 00:05:22.590
and the doctor says, all right,
you should exercise and eat

00:05:22.590 --> 00:05:24.580
well, that's a
normal office visit.

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:26.830
But if you're put on
medication, then somebody

00:05:26.830 --> 00:05:28.930
in some drug company
somewhere in New Jersey

00:05:28.930 --> 00:05:30.330
is going to make a profit.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.670
If you have an
echocardiogram or an EKG

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:35.914
or a catheterization, the
more things that are done,

00:05:35.914 --> 00:05:37.955
the more the system is
reimbursed, all the way up

00:05:37.955 --> 00:05:39.050
to open heart surgery.

00:05:39.050 --> 00:05:42.780
And so the system is basically
financially incentivizing

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:46.140
disease, and it's for every
disease, every problem.

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:48.050
And wellness, which
makes the most sense

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:50.490
that we should be thinking
about encouraging,

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:53.550
really isn't incentivized
in the same way disease is.

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:57.000
And so we basically
wait until it's broken.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:58.800
And so the concept
I've been pushing

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:01.810
is getting America to go.

00:06:01.810 --> 00:06:04.980
Now this is the United States
on the far left-hand side

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:06.139
the graph here.

00:06:06.139 --> 00:06:08.430
Every other Western country
averaged out is in the red.

00:06:08.430 --> 00:06:11.040
So we're spending more
than double every country

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:13.300
in the world on health
care expenditure.

00:06:13.300 --> 00:06:15.220
So with that, I
would think we would

00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:18.330
have the healthiest country
in the world, right?

00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:21.180
How about 28th in
life expectancy?

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:23.150
So we're spending more
than double everybody,

00:06:23.150 --> 00:06:25.000
we're ranked 28th
in life expectancy,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.356
and we're just throwing
money at this problem.

00:06:27.356 --> 00:06:29.730
And even all these different
discussions about Affordable

00:06:29.730 --> 00:06:33.410
Care, et cetera, are a lot about
reducing spending in some way,

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:35.070
but they're not
about the main issue,

00:06:35.070 --> 00:06:37.640
in my opinion, which is
preventing disease, which

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.620
is what we're really
not focusing on.

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:41.750
This is the United
States in 1985.

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:45.550
States reporting less than
10% obesity are in light blue,

00:06:45.550 --> 00:06:47.010
10% to 15% are in
the darker blue.

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:52.490
And let's look what happened,
'86, '87, '88, '89, '90,

00:06:52.490 --> 00:06:56.364
'91-- now 15% to 19%
obesity-- '92, '93,

00:06:56.364 --> 00:07:01.980
'94, '95, '96, '97-- now
greater than 20% obesity-- '98,

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:07.050
'99, 2000, 2001-- greater
than 25% obesity-- 2002,

00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:10.540
2003, 2004, 2005--
greater than 30%

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:15.110
obesity-- 2006,
2007, 2008, 2009.

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:19.100
So basically, if you want to
be skinny move to Colorado

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:21.010
is the answer here.

00:07:21.010 --> 00:07:23.890
But we have this
kind of growing issue

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:28.940
of the cost of inactivity
in our society.

00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:32.040
And as much as I love all the
computer-based everything,

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:35.250
it basically is another way
where people sit at home

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:36.000
and do whatever.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.780
So getting people up and moving
is a huge piece, I think,

00:07:38.780 --> 00:07:41.140
of the equation of
fixing the problem.

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:43.900
So I'm going to talk
to you guys about what

00:07:43.900 --> 00:07:46.160
you can do individually,
what you can do as a company,

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:48.535
and what I think we can start
thinking about as a society

00:07:48.535 --> 00:07:51.210
to try and deal with some of
these issues as we go forth.

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:54.080
So what you can do as an
individual is find something

00:07:54.080 --> 00:07:54.830
you like to do.

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:56.830
If you like to bike in a
group, bike in a group.

00:07:56.830 --> 00:07:58.871
If you like to go run in
a group, run in a group.

00:07:58.871 --> 00:08:00.450
If you're somebody
that says, listen,

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:02.230
I'm so stressed out
at my place and I

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:04.350
want to go run by
myself, that's fine too.

00:08:04.350 --> 00:08:06.007
Whatever it is that
will motivate you,

00:08:06.007 --> 00:08:07.090
that's what you got to do.

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:08.757
So number one is
finding a way to do it.

00:08:08.757 --> 00:08:11.173
And I'm going to talk about
New York City is a great place

00:08:11.173 --> 00:08:13.405
to do that, because we
have a great opportunity

00:08:13.405 --> 00:08:16.240
to increase what's called
our NEAT profiles here.

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:18.819
Now I think nothing
is as helpful as some

00:08:18.819 --> 00:08:21.235
of the different people I see
in my life and take care of.

00:08:21.235 --> 00:08:24.192
I met a guy yesterday
who I'd seen about three

00:08:24.192 --> 00:08:26.650
months before who'd had really
bad back pain and knee pain,

00:08:26.650 --> 00:08:29.210
and he'd gotten opinions
about getting surgery

00:08:29.210 --> 00:08:30.270
on different stuff.

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:32.669
And I said, listen, you are
getting a lot of this problem

00:08:32.669 --> 00:08:34.450
because you're just
completely inactive.

00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:37.490
And if you want to see
somebody's torn meniscus,

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:38.429
get an MRI.

00:08:38.429 --> 00:08:41.200
If you want to see their
herniated disc, get an MRI.

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:44.960
As technology has improved, the
quality of pictures, about half

00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:47.460
of you in this room have a torn
meniscus or a herniated disc

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:48.740
in your back that you
don't even know about

00:08:48.740 --> 00:08:50.640
and I don't care about because
it's not bothering you.

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:52.990
But the problem is if you start
getting tests things start

00:08:52.990 --> 00:08:54.573
showing up, and then
people get things

00:08:54.573 --> 00:08:57.120
done based on those findings,
and it's not good for people.

00:08:57.120 --> 00:08:59.411
This guy, we just got him
working on some strengthening

00:08:59.411 --> 00:09:01.570
and exercise stuff, and
I saw him yesterday.

00:09:01.570 --> 00:09:02.680
He's doing great.

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:06.630
I think that puts a lot of these
things in a better context.

00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:09.210
Because somebody like that that
shows up at a psychiatrist's

00:09:09.210 --> 00:09:10.750
office is probably going
to put on some kind

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:12.910
of antidepressant medication,
in a cardiologist's office

00:09:12.910 --> 00:09:14.493
some kind of blood
pressure medication

00:09:14.493 --> 00:09:16.170
or cholesterol-lowering
medication.

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:17.920
And there's a lot of medicines.

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:20.840
We live in this society where
if you're having sleep problems

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:23.617
your immediate thought is open
the window and that butterfly

00:09:23.617 --> 00:09:25.200
is going to fly and
land on your head,

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:27.616
and you're going have the best
night's sleep of your life.

00:09:27.616 --> 00:09:29.360
Or if you're having
erectile dysfunction,

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:30.380
you just take this medicine.

00:09:30.380 --> 00:09:32.213
You can throw the
football through the tire,

00:09:32.213 --> 00:09:34.550
and life is great
and life is perfect.

00:09:34.550 --> 00:09:36.940
The problem is these
medicines cost a lot of money,

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.460
they have a lot of side
effects, and they're

00:09:39.460 --> 00:09:41.730
often not the best
first-line treatment.

00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:43.955
So getting doctors and
health care professionals

00:09:43.955 --> 00:09:46.360
to start thinking about
prescribing exercise

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:48.996
is a big part of the mission
of what I'm after with this.

00:09:48.996 --> 00:09:49.870
And it's interesting.

00:09:49.870 --> 00:09:52.080
As I mentioned, there's
not a lot of movement

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:53.663
or there hasn't been
a lot of movement

00:09:53.663 --> 00:09:55.950
traditionally in that
direction, despite the fact

00:09:55.950 --> 00:09:59.122
that we had great evidence
on the role of exercise

00:09:59.122 --> 00:10:00.580
for a number of
different problems.

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:02.746
So what I've tried to do
in "Exercise Cure" is start

00:10:02.746 --> 00:10:05.007
with the brain and go down
and look at, all right,

00:10:05.007 --> 00:10:07.090
what's the best study for
depression and exercise?

00:10:07.090 --> 00:10:08.730
There's a big study
done in Norway

00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:11.532
where they took one group of
people in a prospective study

00:10:11.532 --> 00:10:13.740
and they looked at their
symptoms of mild to moderate

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:15.820
depression with
exercise versus drugs,

00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:18.950
and the exercise
guys did better.

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:23.050
So things like anxiety, sleep
problems, self-esteem, memory--

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:24.707
exercise is the only
drug which works

00:10:24.707 --> 00:10:26.540
for Alzheimer's and
dementia, the only drug.

00:10:26.540 --> 00:10:27.740
Despite the billions
of dollars that

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:30.323
have been put towards research,
it's the only drug that works.

00:10:30.323 --> 00:10:32.970
So I think there's a
lot of information that

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:35.187
needs to get out on
this, and part of that

00:10:35.187 --> 00:10:37.270
definitely starts with the
health care profession,

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:40.680
so trying to get physicians and
nurses and nurse practitioners

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:42.880
to start thinking about
prescribing exercise

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:44.690
as part of what
