00:21:22.782 --> 00:21:23.770
All right.

00:21:23.770 --> 00:21:26.730
So what's our
current system doing?

00:21:26.730 --> 00:21:29.160
Some health care
companies, some companies

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:31.350
give you a discount
if you join a gym.

00:21:31.350 --> 00:21:32.060
That's great.

00:21:32.060 --> 00:21:33.544
But all right, so
you join a gym.

00:21:33.544 --> 00:21:34.960
Does that mean
you're going to go?

00:21:34.960 --> 00:21:37.520
I don't know.

00:21:37.520 --> 00:21:40.070
The truth is less than 5%
of Americans are active.

00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:43.350
There was a big study published
of 11 different studies 2012,

00:21:43.350 --> 00:21:45.050
2013.

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:47.860
Motivation came
through incentives.

00:21:47.860 --> 00:21:51.484
If we incentivize people
to move, they moved.

00:21:51.484 --> 00:21:53.900
This is the best study I'm
going to show you in this talk.

00:21:53.900 --> 00:21:56.824
This guy published in "JAMA,"
and he's got a dual appointment

00:21:56.824 --> 00:21:58.240
at the University
of Pennsylvania.

00:21:58.240 --> 00:22:00.520
He's at Wharton and
at the Medical School.

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:03.710
And his whole thing is
looking at financial models

00:22:03.710 --> 00:22:05.470
to incentivize behavior.

00:22:05.470 --> 00:22:09.430
And he took 56 guys who
were very overweight.

00:22:09.430 --> 00:22:12.340
Now they were between
the ages of 40 and 60.

00:22:12.340 --> 00:22:14.390
The truth is if you want
to get either gender

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:16.190
to change what
they're doing, try

00:22:16.190 --> 00:22:18.690
getting a guy to
change his behavior?

00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:19.330
Good luck.

00:22:19.330 --> 00:22:19.830
All right?

00:22:19.830 --> 00:22:22.400
So baseline, it's tough to get
guys to change their behavior.

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:22.899
Fair?

00:22:22.899 --> 00:22:23.690
Fair.

00:22:23.690 --> 00:22:25.677
Now in that we had
these guys that

00:22:25.677 --> 00:22:27.260
had these really
unhealthy health care

00:22:27.260 --> 00:22:28.750
behaviors for a long time.

00:22:28.750 --> 00:22:30.500
They were very sedentary.

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:33.200
And what he did was he set up a
model where basically everybody

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:36.500
got the same intake
information, diet and exercise.

00:22:36.500 --> 00:22:40.110
Now in that, one group they
were weighed every week

00:22:40.110 --> 00:22:43.000
for 16 weeks, and
that's all they got.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.640
One group, he said, listen,
if you lose a pound a week

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:49.070
for 16 weeks, we're going
to give you $5 a week.

00:22:49.070 --> 00:22:50.950
And one group said,
you're going to come in,

00:22:50.950 --> 00:22:52.800
we're going to weigh
you once a week,

00:22:52.800 --> 00:22:54.610
and you get a scratch-off,
like a lottery.

00:22:54.610 --> 00:22:56.568
And if you basically are
at your target weight,

00:22:56.568 --> 00:22:58.180
if you lost a pound
a week, then you

00:22:58.180 --> 00:22:58.960
win what's underneath the thing.

00:22:58.960 --> 00:23:00.335
It was everything
from $5 to $50.

00:23:00.335 --> 00:23:02.820
So some weeks you do good,
and some weeks you do bad.

00:23:02.820 --> 00:23:05.914
At the end of four months, the
guys that got the information

00:23:05.914 --> 00:23:07.330
but didn't get
anything else, they

00:23:07.330 --> 00:23:09.840
were just weighed,
exactly the same weight.

00:23:09.840 --> 00:23:13.620
Both the financial models lost
on average about 17 pounds,

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:15.960
and everybody made
their target goal.

00:23:15.960 --> 00:23:19.350
Now the average diabetic
who has diabetes

00:23:19.350 --> 00:23:22.790
because they're overweight and
takes insulin cost about $350

00:23:22.790 --> 00:23:24.724
per month on medicine.

00:23:24.724 --> 00:23:26.140
These guys were
paid at an average

00:23:26.140 --> 00:23:28.520
of $250 over a four-month
period of time.

00:23:28.520 --> 00:23:29.669
It doesn't take much money.

00:23:29.669 --> 00:23:31.460
It just takes a little
incentive structure.

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:33.570
So different companies are
doing different things,

00:23:33.570 --> 00:23:34.710
everything from using--

00:23:34.710 --> 00:23:35.751
Some of you have Fitbits.

00:23:35.751 --> 00:23:37.360
If you join Humana
Insurance, they

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:39.360
have this Vitality program
where you can sign up

00:23:39.360 --> 00:23:42.122
for the Vitality program
and you get a Fitbit.

00:23:42.122 --> 00:23:44.330
Then they calculate what's
called your Vitality score

00:23:44.330 --> 00:23:45.380
and your Vitality age.

00:23:45.380 --> 00:23:48.920
So you're 35, and your
health care behavior is such

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:52.496
that you may be only
31, or you may be 40.

00:23:52.496 --> 00:23:53.870
And they calculate
how many steps

00:23:53.870 --> 00:23:56.090
you need per day and per week.

00:23:56.090 --> 00:23:57.820
And if you meet
your target goals,

00:23:57.820 --> 00:23:59.780
you pay a little bit less in
your health insurance premium.

00:23:59.780 --> 00:24:01.665
Because why should you
pay more than somebody

00:24:01.665 --> 00:24:02.790
else who's really inactive?

00:24:02.790 --> 00:24:03.610
It doesn't make any sense.

00:24:03.610 --> 00:24:05.200
Plus it'll incentivize
you to do more.

00:24:05.200 --> 00:24:08.350
So there's a lot we're going
to be seeing in this space

00:24:08.350 --> 00:24:11.130
to encourage people
to do the right thing.

00:24:11.130 --> 00:24:12.479
And we do it already.

00:24:12.479 --> 00:24:13.520
Why do people buy houses?

00:24:13.520 --> 00:24:15.820
And why do people do
all kinds of things?

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:17.750
We incentivize marriage
and having kids

00:24:17.750 --> 00:24:19.600
and going into
debt in some ways.

00:24:19.600 --> 00:24:21.090
So our system
already incentivizes

00:24:21.090 --> 00:24:22.366
all these behaviors.

00:24:22.366 --> 00:24:24.240
We're spending so much
money on this problem,

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:27.000
we should be incentivizing
activity and wellness.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:28.700
And so that's I think that is.

